[[Vice Admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice Admiral]] '''Sir (Hugh) Richard (Benest) Janvrin''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSC]] (2 May 1915 - 15 January 1993) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who became [[List of senior officers of the Royal Navy#Deputy Chiefs of the Naval Staff|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]].

==Naval career==
Educated at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], Janvrin joined the [[Royal Navy]] in 1929 and specialised in [[Aerial photography|aerial observation]].<ref name=who>''Who<U+2019>s Who in Naval History: From 1550 to the Present'', Published 2004, Taylor and Francis, ISBN 0-203-01351-4</ref> He served in [[World War II]] and acted as an observer at the [[Battle of Taranto]] in November 1940 for which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSC]].<ref name=who/> 

He was given command of the [[destroyer]] [[HMS Broadsword (D31)|HMS ''Broadsword'']] in 1951, the Second Frigate Squadron in 1957 and the [[aircraft carrier]] [[HMS Victorious (R38)|HMS ''Victorious'']] in 1959.<ref name=who/> He went on to be Flag Officer, Aircraft Carriers in 1964 and [[List of senior officers of the Royal Navy#Deputy Chiefs of the Naval Staff|Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff]] in 1966 before retiring in 1968.<ref>[http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201900-.pdf Royal Navy Appointments]</ref>

He lived at Allen's Close in [[Stroud]] in [[Gloucestershire]].<ref name=peerage>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p25226.htm#i252255 The Peerage.com]</ref>

==Family==
In 1938 he married Nancy Edyth Fielding; they had two sons (Simon and [[Robin Janvrin, Baron Janvrin|Robin]]).<ref name=peerage/>

